# React Component Rules

## Component Declaration

Use **full function declarations**. Arrow functions for components are forbidden.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
const UserProfile = () => { ... };
const UserProfile = (props: Props) => { ... };
export const UserProfile: FC<Props> = () => { ... };

// ✅ GOOD
export function UserProfile() { ... }
export function UserProfile(props: Props) { ... }
```

## Naming

Component names must be descriptive and unambiguous. If a component is used inside another, add a clear prefix.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — unclear what "Item" belongs to
function Item(props: Props) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — explicit context
function OrderListItem(props: Props) { ... }
function OrderListHeader(props: Props) { ... }
```

## Exports

Default exports are forbidden. Always use named exports.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
export default function UserProfile() { ... }

// ✅ GOOD
export function UserProfile() { ... }
```

## Props

Declare props as `interface Props`. Do not prefix the interface with the component name.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
interface UserProfileProps { ... }
type Props = { ... };

// ✅ GOOD
interface Props {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

export function UserProfile(props: Props) { ... }
```

When the component accepts `children`, use `PropsWithChildren`:

```tsx
import { PropsWithChildren } from "react";

// Only children — no extra props
export function Layout(props: PropsWithChildren) { ... }

// Children + other props
interface Props extends PropsWithChildren {
  title: string;
}

export function Layout(props: Props) { ... }
```

## One Component Per File

Each component must live in its own file. Multiple exported components in a single file are forbidden.

## Memoization

Use `useMemo` for expensive computations and derived data. Use `useCallback` for callback functions passed to child components.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — recalculates on every render
const sorted = items.sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));

// ✅ GOOD
const sorted = useMemo(
  () => [...items].sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)),
  [items],
);

// ❌ BAD — new function reference on every render
<ChildComponent onClick={() => handleClick(id)} />;

// ✅ GOOD
const handleItemClick = useCallback(() => handleClick(id), [id]);
<ChildComponent onClick={handleItemClick} />;
```

## Code Quality

- No hacks, workarounds, or TODO-driven code. Write clean, maintainable solutions.
- Avoid `any`. Use proper TypeScript types.
- Avoid unnecessary `useEffect` — derive state from props/state where possible.
